      "text": "A 34-year-old woman presents with 2 days of nausea and vomiting. She has vomited 8-10 times daily and cannot keep down oral fluids. Vital signs show heart rate 105 bpm, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, temperature 37.0°C. Physical examination reveals mild dehydration and mild abdominal discomfort to palpation. Laboratory studies show normal electrolytes and glucose. After receiving 2 liters of IV fluids and two doses of ondansetron, she continues to vomit and cannot tolerate oral intake. What is the most appropriate disposition?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Admit for continued IV therapy and antiemetics"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Discharge home with oral antiemetics and follow-up"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Administer metoclopramide then reassess"
        },
        {
          "id": 4,
          "text": "Place nasogastric tube for decompression"
        },
        {
          "id": 5,
          "text": "Transfer to tertiary care center"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<div><h4 style='color: #34d399; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>A) CORRECT:</h4>Correct – Hospital admission appropriate for this patient with severe <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=7J04vS&anker=Z2f0b48ef2acaab783b03e4c8d2404f90\" data-learningcard-id=\"7J04vS\" data-anker=\"Z2f0b48ef2acaab783b03e4c8d2404f90\">vomiting</a> refractory to <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=qm0Cgg&anker=Zf172aa3c3f8399678e63b0616b911cfc\" data-learningcard-id=\"qm0Cgg\" data-anker=\"Zf172aa3c3f8399678e63b0616b911cfc\" data-section-id=\"hEbcvv\">antiemetic therapy</a>.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>B) INCORRECT:</h4>Discharge with oral medications is inappropriate for a patient who cannot tolerate oral intake and continues to vomit despite treatment.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>C) INCORRECT:</h4>While trying an alternative antiemetic is reasonable, this approach delays definitive disposition when the patient already meets criteria for admission due to refractory symptoms and inability to maintain oral intake.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>D) INCORRECT:</h4>\n<a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=X809O3&anker=Zbea81401ee2fc0a96932cb6db23dc6f5\" data-learningcard-id=\"X809O3\" data-anker=\"Zbea81401ee2fc0a96932cb6db23dc6f5\" data-sememe-id=\"D-11zj0\">Nasogastric tube placement</a> is indicated for specific conditions like <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=230T3f&anker=Zd632dab0bd82fad268f38b319729e1c3\" data-learningcard-id=\"230T3f\" data-anker=\"Zd632dab0bd82fad268f38b319729e1c3\" data-sememe-id=\"2O0T7T\">bowel obstruction</a> but is not appropriate in this stable patient.</div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>E) INCORRECT:</h4>Transfer to a tertiary center is unnecessary for this hemodynamically stable patient with no evidence of pathology requiring specialized care.</div>",
